description: The Brief Psychiatric Rating Scale (BPRS) has been widely used in PD psychiatric clinical trials and is the easiest/shortest to administer. It was initially developed for schizophrenia. The instrument should be used in cognitively intact subjects and does not require an informant.

cdes.cdeName: Brief Psychiatric Rating Scale (BPRS) - somatic concern score
cdes.definitionDescription: The score of the participant's/subject's somatic concern, as part of the Brief Psychiatric Rating Scale (BPRS) form.
cdes.questionText: Somatic Concern Preoccupation with physical health fear of physical illness hypochondriasis.
cdes.permissibleDescription: Not assessed;Not present;Very mild;Mild;Moderate;Moderately severe;Severe;Extremely severe;
cdes.instructions: Record the score for the term that best describes the participant's/subject's condition
cdes.referrences: Fernandez et al. Scales to Assess Psychosis in Parkinson's Disease. Mov Disord. 2008 Mar 15;23(4):484-500.

cdes.cdeName: Brief Traumatic Brain Injury Screen (BTBIS) - Injury during deployment type
cdes.definitionDescription: The type of injury sustained during deployment, as part of the Brief Traumatic Brain Injury Screen (BTBIS).
cdes.questionText: Did you have any injury(ies) during your deployment from any of the following:
cdes.permissibleDescription: fragment;Bullet;Vehicular (any type of vehicle, including airplane);Fall;Blast (Improvised Explosive Device, RPG, Land Mine, Grenade, Etc.);Other, specify;Not applicable;
cdes.referrences: Schwab, K. A., Baker, G., Ivins, B., Sluss-Tiller, M., Lux, W., & Warden, D. (2006). The Brief Traumatic Brain Injury Screen (BTBIS): Investigating the validity of a self-report instrument for detecting traumatic brain injury (TBI) in troops returning from deployment in Afghanistan and Iraq. Neurology, 66(5)(Supp. 2), A235. www.DVBIC.org

cdes.cdeName: Brief Traumatic Brain Injury Screen (BTBIS) - Injury result type
cdes.definitionDescription: The type of result from injury during deployment, as part of the Brief Traumatic Brain Injury Screen (BTBIS).
cdes.questionText: Did any injury received wihle you were deployed result in any of the follow?
cdes.permissibleDescription: Being dazed, confused, or 'seeing stars';Not remembering the injury;Losing consciousness (knocked out) for less than a minute;Losing consciousness for 1-20 minutes;Losing consciousness for longer than 20 minutes;Having any symptoms of concussion afterward (such as headache, dizziness, irritability, etc.);Head injury;None of the above;
cdes.instructions: Endorsement of first 5 items meets criteria for positive TBI screen. Check all that apply.

crfModuleGuideline: CAGE Substance Abuse Screening Tool Questionnaire

cdes.cdeName: CAGE Substance Abuse Screening Tool Questionnaire - Need decrease alcohol consumption indicator
cdes.definitionDescription: The indicator related to feelings toward the need to cut down on the amount of alcohol consumed, as part of the CAGE Substance Abuse Screening Tool Questionnaire.
cdes.questionText: Have you ever felt you should Cut down on your drinking?
cdes.permissibleDescription: No;Yes;
cdes.instructions: Item responses on the CAGE are scored 0 or 1, with a higher score an indication of alcohol problems. A total score of 2 or greater is considered clinically significant.
cdes.referrences: JA Ewing “Detecting Alcoholism: The CAGE Questionnaire” JAMA 252: 1905-1907, 1984.
cdes.aliasesForVariableName: Aliases for variable name not defined
cdes.crfModuleGuideline: CAGE Substance Abuse Screening Tool Questionnaire

cdes.definitionDescription: The indicator related to feeling annoyed due to others  criticizing their alcohol consumption, as part of the CAGE Substance Abuse Screening Tool Questionnaire.
cdes.questionText: Have people Annoyed you by criticizing your drinking?
cdes.permissibleDescription: No;Yes;
cdes.instructions: Item responses on the CAGE are scored 0 or 1, with a higher score an indication of alcohol problems. A total score of 2 or greater is considered clinically significant.

description: California Verbal Learning Test Second Edition (CVLT-II)

The CBI-R is a global measure of change, capturing cognitive, physical, mood, sleep, and eating changes in addition to FTD-type behavior/personality change. The measure captures information about the level of functioning in the past month, and does not specify change across a period of time.

cdes.cdeName: Cambridge Behavioural Inventory Revised (CBI-R) - poor daily memory frequency score

crfModuleGuideline: Cambridge Brain Repair Centre (BRC) HD Sleep Questionnaire
description: The Cambridge Brain Repair Centre HD Sleep Questionnaire is a newly created instrument specifically designed for use with HD patients, this questionnaire was, in part, based on recent questionnaires used in Parkinson's disease. It contains 45 questions that focus on many aspects of sleep: duration, quality, quality of life, and abnormal sleep behaviors. The authors group the questions into four themed subcategories: quality of sleep, motor activity, abnormal nocturnal behavior and other aspects of disturbed sleep. The authors of this instrument have written comprehensive reviews of the literature in HD and have conducted prior studies of sleep in HD.

crfModuleGuideline: Cambridge-Hopkins Restless Legs Syndrome Diagnostic Questionnaire (CH-RLSQ)
description: The Cambridge-Hopkins diagnostic questionnaire for restless leg syndrome (CH-RLSq) was developed with several iterations to include items covering the basic diagnostic features of RLS and to provide some basic differential diagnosis.

cdes.definitionDescription: The indicator of whether or not the participant/subject has recurrent uncomfortable feelings or sensations in their legs while sitting or lying down, as part of the Cambridge-Hopkins Restless Legs Syndrome Diagnostic Questionnaire (CH-RLSQ) form.
cdes.questionText: Do you have, or have you had, recurrent uncomfortable feelings or sensations in your legs while sitting or lying down?
cdes.permissibleDescription: Yes;No;
cdes.instructions: If you answered YES to either Question 1 or 2 continue Question 3. If you answered NO to BOTH stop here .
cdes.referrences: Allen et al. Validation of the self-completed Cambridge-Hopkins questionnaire (CH-RLSq) for ascertainment of restless legs syndrome (RLS) in a population survey. Sleep Medicine 2009;10(10):1097-1100.

cdes.definitionDescription: The value of how many of the participant's/subject's own children the participant/subject is unsure of whether they have these feelings, as part of the Cambridge-Hopkins Restless Legs Syndrome Diagnostic Questionnaire (CH-RLSQ) form.
cdes.questionText: Thinking about your own children, how many of these children do you not know if they have similar feelings in their legs?
cdes.instructions: Please write in the number that do and do not have these feelings, and the number for whom you don’t know whether they have these feelings. If you do not have children or siblings, please indicate so.

Contains data elements pertaining to cardiac end points. (Examples of CDEs included: FA End Points Hospitalizations in past year, FA End Points Start Date of hospitalization)

cdes.cdeName: American College of Cardiology and the American Heart Association heart failure stage
cdes.definitionDescription: Stage of the participant/subject's heart failure according to the American College of Cardiology (ACC) and the American Heart Association (AHA) Stage of Heart Failure
cdes.questionText: Classify the subject using the ACC/AHA Stage of Heart Failure
cdes.permissibleDescription: A - Patients at high risk of developing HF because of the presence of conditions that are strongly associated with the development of HF, such patients have no identified structural or functional abnormalities of the pericardium, myocardium, or cardiac valves and have never shown signs or symptoms of HF;B - Patients who have developed structural heart disease that is strongly associated with the development of HF but who have never shown signs or symptoms of HF;C - Patients who have current or prior symptoms of HF associated with underlying structural heart disease;D - Patients with advanced structural heart disease and marked symptoms of HF at rest despite maximal medical therapy and who require specialized interventions;
cdes.referrences: Hunt SA, Abraham WT, Chin MH, Feldman AM, Francis GS, et al. (2005) ACC/AHA 2005 Guideline Update for the Diagnosis and Management of Chronic Heart Failure in the Adult A Report of the American College of Cardiology/American Heart Association Task Force on Practice Guidelines (Writing Committee to Update the 2001 Guidelines for the Evaluation and Management of Heart Failure). Circulatio, 112,e154-e235.

The Center for Epidemiologic Studies Depression Scale (CES-D) is a widely used screening scale for depression. It consists of six subscales of depressed mood, feelings of guilt and worthlessness, feelings of helplessness and hopelessness, psychomotor retardation, loss of appetite, and sleep disturbance. The CES-D queries a patient's depression symptoms in the last week, with each question is scored on a 4-point Likert scale ranging from 0 (rarely/none of the time) to 3 (most/all of the time). Scores for items 4, 8, 12, and 16 are reversed before summing all items to yield a total score. A score of 16 or higher has been used to indicate highly depressive symptoms.

cdes.permissibleDescription: Rarely or none of the time (less than 1 day);Some or a little of the time (1-2 days);Occasionally or a moderate amount of the time (3-4 days);Most or all of the time (5-7 days);
cdes.referrences: Radloff, L.S. (1977). The CES-D scale: A self report depression scale for research in the general population. Applied Psychological Measurement 1: 385-401.

description: The Center for Epidemiologic Studies Depression Scale (CES-D) is a widely used screening scale for depression. It consists of six subscales of depressed mood, feelings of guilt and worthlessness, feelings of helplessness and hopelessness, psychomotor retardation, loss of appetite, and sleep disturbance. The CES-D queries a patient's depression symptoms in the last week, with each question is scored on a 4-point Likert scale ranging from 0 (rarely/none of the time) to 3 (most/all of the time). Scores for items 4, 8, 12, and 16 are reversed before summing all items to yield a total score. A score of 16 or higher has been used to indicate highly depressive symptoms.

It consists of six subscales of depressed mood, feelings of guilt and worthlessness, feelings of helplessness and hopelessness, psychomotor retardation, loss of appetite, and sleep disturbance. The CES-D queries a patient's depression symptoms in the last week, with each question is scored on a 4-point Likert scale ranging from 0 (rarely/none of the time) to 3 (most/all of the time). Scores for items 4, 8, 12, and 16 are reversed before summing all items to yield a total score. A score of 16 or higher has been used to indicate highly depressive symptoms.

cdes.cdeName: Center for Epidemiologic Studies Depression Scale (CES-D) - total score
cdes.definitionDescription: CES-D Total Score - summation of the scores for the 20 items (0-60)
cdes.instructions:
Refer to instructions on form.  Higher scores indicate more depressive symptoms.  A total score of 16 or higher is considered depressed.

Supplemental - Highly Recommended based on study type, disease stage and disease type

description: The Center for Epidemiologic Studies Depression Scale (CES-D) is a widely used screening scale for depression. It consists of six subscales of depressed mood, feelings of guilt and worthlessness, feelings of helplessness and hopelessness, psychomotor retardation, loss of appetite, and sleep disturbance. The CES-D queries a patient's depression symptoms in the last week, with each question is scored on a 4-point Likert scale ranging from 0 (rarely/none of the time) to 3 (most/all of the time). Scores for items 4, 8, 12, and 16 are reversed before summing all items to yield a total score. A score of 16 or higher has been used to indicate highly depressive symptoms.

description: The Center for Epidemiologic Studies Depression Scale (CES-D) is a widely used screening scale for depression. It consists of six subscales of depressed mood, feelings of guilt and worthlessness, feelings of helplessness and hopelessness, psychomotor retardation, loss of appetite, and sleep disturbance. The CES-D queries a patient's depression symptoms in the last week, with each question is scored on a 4-point Likert scale ranging from 0 (rarely/none of the time) to 3 (most/all of the time). Scores for items 4, 8, 12, and 16 are reversed before summing all items to yield a total score. A score of 16 or higher has been used to indicate highly depressive symptoms.

description: The Center for Epidemiologic Studies Depression Scale (CES-D) is a widely used screening scale for depression. It consists of six subscales of depressed mood, feelings of guilt and worthlessness, feelings of helplessness and hopelessness, psychomotor retardation, loss of appetite, and sleep disturbance. The CES-D queries a patient's depression symptoms in the last week, with each question is scored on a 4-point Likert scale ranging from 0 (rarely/none of the time) to 3 (most/all of the time). Scores for items 4, 8, 12, and 16 are reversed before summing all items to yield a total score. A score of 16 or higher has been used to indicate highly depressive symptoms.

cdes.definitionDescription: CES-D Total Score - summation of the scores for the 20 items (0-60)
cdes.instructions: zero for answer in the first column, 1 for answers in the second column, 2 for answers in the third column, 3 for answers in the fourth column. crfModuleGuideline: Center for Neurologic Study - Lability Scale for pseudobulbar affect (PBA)
description: Devised to provide a short, self- report measure of affective lability in patients with ALS, to cover both labile tearfulness and laughter. Items were initially generated from interviews with patients identified as having affective lability and their caregivers.

cdes.cdeName: Center for Neurologic Study-Lability Scale (CNS-LS) - fine tearful scale
cdes.definitionDescription: Scale used to measure the degree to which the participant/subject felt he became tearful over something small or for no reason during this past week, as part of the Center for Neurologic Study-Lability Scale (CNS-LS) for pseudobulbar affect (PBA) questionnaire.
cdes.questionText: There are times when I feel fine 1 minute, and then I’ll become tearful the next over something small or for no reason at all.
cdes.permissibleDescription: Applies never;Applies rarely;Applies occasionally;Applies frequently;Applies most of the time;
cdes.instructions: Please write the number that describes the degree to which each item applies to you DURING THE PAST WEEK. Write only 1 number for each item.
cdes.referrences: Moore SR, Gresham L, Bromberg MB, Kasarkis E, Smith RA (1997). A self report measure of affective lability. J. Neurol Neurosurg Psychiatry 1997;63:89-93.  Brooks BR, Thisted RA, Appel SH, Bradley WG, Olney RK, Berg JE, Pope LE, and Smith RA (2004) Treatment of pseudobulbar affect in ALS with dextromethorphan/quinidine: a randomized trial. Neurology 63(8):1364-70.

cdes.crfModuleGuideline: Center for Neurologic Study - Lability Scale for pseudobulbar affect (PBA)

cdes.cdeName: Center for Neurologic Study-Lability Scale (CNS-LS) - amused easily not funny scale
cdes.definitionDescription: Scale used to measure the degree to which the participant/subject felt he became amused easily or were amused by things that weren't really funny during this past week, as part of the Center for Neurologic Study-Lability Scale (CNS-LS) for pseudobulbar affect (PBA) questionnaire.
cdes.questionText: Others have told me that I seem to become amused very easily or that I seem to become amused about things that really aren’t funny.
cdes.permissibleDescription: Applies never;Applies rarely;Applies occasionally;Applies frequently;Applies most of the time;
cdes.instructions: Please write the number that describes the degree to which each item applies to you DURING THE PAST WEEK. Write only 1 number for each item.
